To demonstrate the robustness of the proposed model in end-to-end text-to-speech synthesis, we compare FastDiff-TTS with other neural TTS systems, including 1) GT, the ground truth audio; 2) GT (voc.), where we first convert the ground truth audio into mel-spectrograms, and then convert the mel-spectrograms back to audio using FastDiff; 3) PortaSpeech 
              (
              )
             + FastDiff: vocoder cascaded with mel-spectrogram generation using the most popular non-autoregressive TTS models; 4) FastSpeech 2s 
              (
              )
            : the extension of FastSpeech 2 to fully end-to-end text-to-waveform generation with multi-task learning; 5) WaveGrad 2 
              (
              )
            : a diffusion probabilistic model to generate waveforms via gradient estimation. The results are shown in Table : FastDiff-TTS could surpass competing end-to-end speech synthesis models and match the voice quality of the state-of-the-art cascaded TTS systems, demonstrating that FastDiff-TTS is efficient in simplifying the overall text-to-speech synthesis pipeline.
